ectly aligned with our approach are limited. For instance, eWER Ali and Renals (2018) and eWER2 Ali and Renals (2020) estimate error rates based on the input signal, which differs from our approach. In contrast, we incorporate the model’s output transcript into the error rate approximation function. The most closely related recent works are WERBERT Sheshadri et al. (2021a) and eWER3 Chowdhury and Ali (2023), which share a similar pipeline. Both use encoders for text, speech, and other data, followed by a regression model trained in an end-to-end setting. Since eWER3 is the more recent of the two, we use it as our baseline. In eWER3, the speech encoder is wav2vec2 Baevski et al. (2020), and the text encoder is roberta-base Liu et al. (2019), with a regression model [...] ## 3 Methodology\n\nWe present a scalable and robust method to approximate ASR performance metrics using multimodal unified embeddings, proxy references, and regression models. The primary goal is to eliminate reliance on ground-truth labels, enabling performance evaluation in label-scarce scenarios. The pipeline consists of three components: representation similarity in a unified speech-text embedding space, agreement with a high-quality proxy reference, and a regression model trained on these features to predict ASR metrics. Our pipeline diagram is shown in Figure 1.\n\n### 3.1 Similarity in Unified Representation Space", "score": 0.6701125, "raw_content": "# On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\n\n###### Abstract\n\nRecent advances in speech foundation models are largely driven by scaling both model size and data, enabling them to perform a wide range of tasks, including speech recognition. Traditionally, ASR models are evaluated using metrics like Word Error Rate (WER) and Character Error Rate (CER), which depend on ground truth labels. As a result of limited labeled data from diverse domains and testing conditions, the true generalization capabilities of these models beyond standard benchmarks remain unclear. Moreover, labeling data is both costly and time-consuming. To address this, we propose a novel label-free approach for approximating ASR performance metrics, eliminating the need for ground truth labels. Our method utilizes multimodal embeddings in a unified space for speech and transcription representations, combined with a high-quality proxy model to compute proxy metrics. These features are used to train a regression model to predict key ASR metrics like Word Error Rate (WER) and Character Error Rate (CER). We experiment with over 40 models across 14 datasets representing both standard and in-the-wild testing conditions. Our results show that we approximate the metrics within a single-digit absolute difference across all experimental configurations, outperforming the most recent baseline by more than 50%.\n\nOn the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\n\nAbdul Waheed1 \n     Hanin Atwany2 \n     Rita Singh1 \n     Bhiksha Raj1\n\n1Carnegie Mellon University     \n2MBZUAI\n\n{abdulw,bhiksha,rsingh}@cs.cmu.edu        hanin.atwany@mbzuai.ac.ae\n\n## 1 Introduction\n\nAutomatic Speech Recognition (ASR) models have made significant advancements in recent years, achieving near-human performance on several standard evaluation benchmarks (Radford et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib41); Seamless Communication et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib49); Communication et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib11); [Harper et al.,](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib20) , inter alia). These models are typically evaluated using metrics like Word Error Rate (WER) and Character Error Rate (CER) Likhomanenko et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib29)), which are essential for assessing model performance.\n\nHowever, these metrics are dependent on ground truths, which are often scarce in resource-constrained environments, and human labeling is both costly and time-consuming. To mitigate this challenge, several reference-free evaluation methods are proposed Yuksel et al. ([2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib65)); Kalgaonkar et al. ([2015](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib25)); Swarup et al. ([2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib53)); Qiu et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib40)); Del-Agua et al. ([2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib12)); Raj et al. ([2011](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib43)). While these approaches eliminate the reliance on labeled data, they primarily offer relative assessments of transcription quality, rather than providing precise error counts or rates. As a result, their applicability in real-world scenarios, where actionable performance metrics are crucial for further model refinement and deployment, is limited.\n\nGiven the limitations of both methods, approximating ASR metrics has emerged as a promising alternative for label-free evaluation Chowdhury and Ali ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib10)); Sheshadri et al. ([2021b](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib51)); Ali and Renals ([2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib1)). This approach typically involves training regression Jalalvand et al. ([2016](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib22)) and/or classification models Sheshadri et al. ([2021a](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib50)) on top of speech and text encoders. While this method offers a close approximation of error metrics, several important questions remain unresolved. Specifically, an approximation model trained on dataset sampled from D𝐷Ditalic\\_D to predict ASR metrics for a source model M𝑀Mitalic\\_M must be evaluated under diverse conditions: 1) on test data that is IID (independent and identically distributed) sampled from D𝐷Ditalic\\_D; 2) on out-of-distribution (OOD) data representing diverse domains and recording conditions; 3) on IID data, but transcription from a target model T𝑇Titalic\\_T; and 4) on OOD data with transcriptions from a target model T𝑇Titalic\\_T. Most prior works Chowdhury and Ali ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib10)); Sheshadri et al. ([2021b](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib51)) focus primarily on the first condition. Moreover, recent advancements in multimodal foundation models offer new opportunities to directly train regression models on unified speech and text embeddings.\n\nTo address these critical research gaps, we propose a novel framework for approximating the performance of a wide range of ASR models, both on standard benchmarks and in-the-wild scenarios. Specifically, we compute the similarity between speech and text embeddings in a unified space, capturing the semantic alignment between the two modalities. Additionally, we incorporate a high-quality reference model as a proxy, based on the intuition that agreement with a reliable proxy correlates with transcription quality, as shown in prior works Waheed et al. ([2025](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib59)). These features are then used to train a regression model to predict key ASR metrics, such as WER, CER, and absolute word and character error counts.\n\nIn summary, our work represents one of the most comprehensive studies to date on approximating ASR metrics at scale, in terms of both data and model coverage. Our proposed approach serves as a reference-free evaluation particularly suited for label-scarce scenarios. Beyond evaluation, our method is especially valuable for tasks such as pseudo-labeling, where high-quality transcriptions are essential for downstream applications like knowledge distillation Waheed et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib58)); Gandhi et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib17)).\n\nOur contributions are as follows:\n\nWe evaluate over 40 ASR models across 14 diverse evaluation setups, including both standard benchmarks and domain-specific, unseen conditions followed by training regression models to approximate ASR metrics.\n\nWe compare our approach with the most recent work on approximating ASR metrics and demonstrate over a 100% improvement against the strong baseline.\n\nWe conduct a rigorous ablation study to analyze the impact of different experimental configurations, providing deeper insights into the robustness of our approach. Our findings show that our method is resilient to diverse evaluation setups and requires only a small amount of training data.\n\nOutline. The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section [2](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S2 \"2 Related Work ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") reviews related work. Section [3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3 \"3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") presents our proposed methodology. Sections [4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S4 \"4 Experiments ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") and [5](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S5 \"5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") detail our experimental setup, results, and ablation study, respectively. Section [6](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S6 \"6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") concludes the paper and outlines future directions.\n\nReproducibility. We are committed to making all code, data, and logs available upon acceptance.\n\n## 2 Related Work\n\nAutomatic speech recognition (ASR) has seen remarkable progress in recent years, driven by advances in deep learning and the availability of extensive training datasets Radford et al. ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib41)); Communication et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib11)). Transformer Vaswani et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib57)) based models, in particular, have significantly contributed to these developments by effectively capturing long-range dependencies and contextual nuances in speech, achieving state-of-the-art (SOTA) performance across diverse benchmarks Kheddar et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib27)); Dhanjal and Singh ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib13)); Zimerman and Wolf ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib66)). While traditional evaluation metrics like Word Error Rate (WER) and Character Error Rate (CER) are de-facto evaluation metrics in benchmarking ASR systems Lin et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib30)); Park et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib38)), scenarios where ground truth transcriptions are unavailable have caught interest in reference-free ASR evaluation methods Karbasi and Kolossa ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib26)); Wang et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib61)); Kuhn et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib28)).\n\nReference-free ASR evaluation methods aim to estimate ASR performance without requiring ground truth transcriptions Ospanov et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib35)). Earlier approaches rely on heuristic features or metadata such as speaker demographics, background noise, and linguistic characteristics Litman et al. ([2000](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib31)); Yoon et al. ([2010](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib63)), limiting their applicability across varied contexts. However, recent advancements focus on deep learning-based frameworks, such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) Elloumi et al. ([2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib15)) and contrastive learning methhods Yuksel et al. ([2023a](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib64)), to predict ASR quality directly from encoded speech and text. For instance, methods like NoRefER Yuksel et al. ([2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib65)) employ Siamese architectures fine-tuned on ASR hypotheses, achieving high correlation with traditional metrics and improving WER by optimizing hypothesis ensembling Park et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib38)).\n\nEfforts to approximate ASR metrics explore hybrid approaches that combine traditional and reference-free methods, such as leveraging word confidence scores, linguistic embeddings, or post-processing adaptations to estimate WER and CER without explicit references Ali and Renals ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib2), [2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib1)); Kuhn et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib28)); Negri et al. ([2014](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib33)). However, these approaches often suffer from reliance on specific ASR models or domain characteristics, limiting their generalizability. Unlike existing methods, our work addresses these limitations by introducing a robust, model and data-agnostic framework that evaluates ASR outputs across diverse datasets and configurations, emphasizing adaptability to unseen domains and variations.\n\n## 3 Methodology\n\nWe present a scalable and robust method to approximate ASR performance metrics using multimodal unified embeddings, proxy references, and regression models. The primary goal is to eliminate reliance on ground-truth labels, enabling performance evaluation in label-scarce scenarios. The pipeline consists of three components: representation similarity in a unified speech-text embedding space, agreement with a high-quality proxy reference, and a regression model trained on these features to predict ASR metrics. Our pipeline diagram is shown in Figure [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3.F1 \"Figure 1 ‣ 3.2 Agreement with a Proxy Reference ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\n### 3.1 Similarity in Unified Representation Space\n\nThe foundation of our approach is the SONAR model Duquenne et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib14)), a state-of-the-art multimodal (speech-text) model trained to produce unified embeddings for both speech and text inputs. Let xspeechsubscript𝑥speechx\\_{\\text{speech}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT represent the input speech signal and xtextsubscript𝑥textx\\_{\\text{text}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT denote the corresponding ASR-generated transcription. SONAR maps these inputs to a shared embedding space, generating espeechsubscript𝑒speeche\\_{\\text{speech}}italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT and etextsubscript𝑒texte\\_{\\text{text}}italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT:\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | espeech=fSONAR⁢(xspeech),etext=fSONAR⁢(xtext)formulae-sequencesubscript𝑒speechsubscript𝑓SONARsubscript𝑥speechsubscript𝑒textsubscript𝑓SONARsubscript𝑥texte\\_{\\text{speech}}=f\\_{\\text{SONAR}}(x\\_{\\text{speech}}),\\quad e\\_{\\text{text}}=f\\_% {\\text{SONAR}}(x\\_{\\text{text}})italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic\\_f start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT SONAR end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) , italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic\\_f start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT SONAR end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) |  | (1) |\n\nwhere fSONARsubscript𝑓SONARf\\_{\\text{SONAR}}italic\\_f start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT SONAR end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT represents the embedding model. The alignment between these embeddings is quantified using cosine similarity:\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | Similarity⁢(xspeech,xtext)=espeech⋅etext‖espeech‖⁢‖etext‖Similaritysubscript𝑥speechsubscript𝑥text⋅subscript𝑒speechsubscript𝑒textnormsubscript𝑒speechnormsubscript𝑒text\\text{Similarity}(x\\_{\\text{speech}},x\\_{\\text{text}})=\\frac{e\\_{\\text{speech}}% \\cdot e\\_{\\text{text}}}{\\|e\\_{\\text{speech}}\\|\\|e\\_{\\text{text}}\\|}Similarity ( italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = divide start\\_ARG italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ⋅ italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_ARG start\\_ARG ∥ italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT speech end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∥ ∥ italic\\_e start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∥ end\\_ARG |  | (2) |\n\nThe similarity metric serves as an indicator of transcription quality, with higher values suggest better alignment between speech and text representations.\n\n### 3.2 Agreement with a Proxy Reference\n\nTo complement the similarity score, we utilize proxy references generated by a high-quality ASR model, denoted as xproxysubscript𝑥proxyx\\_{\\text{proxy}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT proxy end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The comparison between the ASR-generated transcription xtextsubscript𝑥textx\\_{\\text{text}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT and the proxy reference xproxysubscript𝑥proxyx\\_{\\text{proxy}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT proxy end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT is quantified using Word Error Rate (pWER) and Character Error Rate (pCER) as defined in Appendix [A.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS1 \"A.1 Methodology ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\nThese metrics assess transcription quality by comparing it with a reliable proxy reference, without using ground-truth labels at any stage. Proxy references are dynamically selected by profiling 41 models across datasets and ranking them by average performance. For each target ASR model, the reference is the highest-ranking model other than the target itself. For example, if whisper-large-v3 ranks highest, the reference for whisper will be the second-best model. This ensures the proxy reference is both relevant and reliable for evaluating the target model.\n\n![Refer to caption](x1.png)\n\n### 3.3 Regression Model for Metric Prediction\n\nThe extracted features, including similarity scores and proxy metrics, are concatenated to form the input to a regression model. Let z=[Similarity,pWER/pCER]𝑧SimilaritypWERpCERz=[\\text{Similarity},\\text{pWER}/\\text{pCER}]italic\\_z = [ Similarity , pWER / pCER ] represent the feature vector. The regression model g𝑔gitalic\\_g estimates the ASR metrics y^^𝑦\\hat{y}over^ start\\_ARG italic\\_y end\\_ARG, denoted as aWER and/or aCER:\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | y^=g⁢(z)^𝑦𝑔𝑧\\hat{y}=g(z)over^ start\\_ARG italic\\_y end\\_ARG = italic\\_g ( italic\\_z ) |  | (3) |\n\nThe regression model is an ensemble of Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, and Histogram-based Gradient Boosting regressors. Each base model is fine-tuned via grid search for hyperparameter optimization. The ensemble is trained to minimize the mean absolute error between predicted and ground-truth metrics. Additionally, a ridge regression model with non-negativity constraints is included in the ensemble to ensure predictions remain within valid ranges. Additional details of our regression pipeline are provided in Section [4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S4 \"4 Experiments ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), with hyperparameter details in Appendix [A.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS4 \"A.4 Experiments ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\n### 3.4 Evaluation\n\nWe evaluate the regression model’s performance across four setups, including IID and OOD data and different model configurations. Specifically, we train our regression model on o