il Panayotov et al. 2015. Librispeech: An ASR cor-pus based on public domain audio books. In 2015 IEEE Int. Conf. on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Pro-cessing (ICASSP), pages 5206–5210.\nChanho Park et al. 2023. Fast word error rate estimation using self-supervised representations for speech and text. arXiv preprint arXiv:2310.08225.\nDouglas B. Paul and Janet M. Baker. 1992. The de-sign for the Wall Street Journal-based CSR corpus.\nIn Speech and Natural Language: Proc. of a Work-shop Held at Harriman, New York, February 23-26, 1992.\nDaniel Povey, Xiaohui Zhang, and Sanjeev Khudanpur.\n2015. Parallel training of DNNs with natural gradient and parameter averaging. Presented at Int. Conf. on Learning Representations (ICLR) workshop.\nDaniel Povey et al. 2016. Purely sequence-trained neu-ral networks for ASR based on Lattice-Free MMI. In Proc. Interspeech 2016, pages 2751–2755.\nAlec Radford et al. Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision.\nOpenAI., https://cdn.ope-nai.com/papers/whisper.pdf (Accessed: Jun 22, 2023).\nChandan K A Reddy, Vishak Gopal, and Ross Cutler.\n2022. DNSMOS P.835: A non-intrusive perceptual objective speech quality metric to evaluate noise sup-pressors. In IEEE Int. Conf. on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), pages 886–890.\nLucia Specia et al. 2018. Quality estimation for machine translation, volume 11. Springer.\nPawel Swietojanski, Arnab Ghoshal, and Steve Renals.\n2013. Revisiting hybrid and GMM-HMM system com-bination techniques. In IEEE Int. Conf. on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing, pages 6744–6748.\nChrysoula Zerva et al. 2022. Findings of the WMT 2022 shared task on quality estimation. In Proc. of 7th Conf.\non Machine Translation (WMT), pages 69–99, Abu Dhabi, UAE (Hybrid). Assoc. for Comput. Linguist."}, {"url": "https://www.isca-archive.org/interspeech_2020/ali20_interspeech.html", "title": "ISCA Archive - Word Error Rate Estimation Without ASR Output: e-WER2", "content": "Measuring the performance of automatic speech recognition (ASR) systems\nrequires manually transcribed data in order to compute the word error\nrate (WER), which is often time-consuming and expensive. In this paper,\nwe continue our effort in estimating WER using acoustic, lexical and\nphonotactic features. Our novel approach to estimate the WER uses a\nmultistream end-to-end architecture. We report results for systems\nusing internal speech decoder features (glass-box), systems without\nspeech decoder features (black-box), and for systems without having\naccess to the ASR system (no-box). The no-box system learns joint acoustic-lexical\nrepresentation from phoneme recognition results along with MFCC acoustic\nfeatures to estimate WER. Considering WER per sentence, our no-box [...] system achieves 0.56 Pearson correlation with the reference evaluation\nand 0.24 root mean square error (RMSE) across 1,400 sentences. The\nestimated overall WER by e-WER2 is 30.9% for a three hours test set,\nwhile the WER computed using the reference transcriptions was 28.5%. [...] `@inproceedings{ali20_interspeech,\ntitle = {{Word Error Rate Estimation Without ASR Output: e-WER2}},\nauthor = {Ahmed Ali and Steve Renals},\nyear = {2020},\nbooktitle = {{Interspeech 2020}},\npages = {616--620},\ndoi = {10.21437/Interspeech.2020-2357},\nissn = {2958-1796},\n}`\n\nCite as: Ali, A., Renals, S. (2020) Word Error Rate Estimation Without ASR Output: e-WER2. Proc. Interspeech 2020, 616-620, doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2020-2357", "score": 0.42005292, "raw_content": "### Word Error Rate Estimation Without ASR Output: e-WER2\n\n##### Ahmed Ali, Steve Renals\n\nMeasuring the performance of automatic speech recognition (ASR) systems\nrequires manually transcribed data in order to compute the word error\nrate (WER), which is often time-consuming and expensive. In this paper,\nwe continue our effort in estimating WER using acoustic, lexical and\nphonotactic features. Our novel approach to estimate the WER uses a\nmultistream end-to-end architecture. We report results for systems\nusing internal speech decoder features (glass-box), systems without\nspeech decoder features (black-box), and for systems without having\naccess to the ASR system (no-box). The no-box system learns joint acoustic-lexical\nrepresentation from phoneme recognition results along with MFCC acoustic\nfeatures to estimate WER. Considering WER per sentence, our no-box\nsystem achieves 0.56 Pearson correlation with the reference evaluation\nand 0.24 root mean square error (RMSE) across 1,400 sentences. The\nestimated overall WER by e-WER2 is 30.9% for a three hours test set,\nwhile the WER computed using the reference transcriptions was 28.5%.\n\n`@inproceedings{ali20_interspeech,\ntitle = {{Word Error Rate Estimation Without ASR Output: e-WER2}},\nauthor = {Ahmed Ali and Steve Renals},\nyear = {2020},\nbooktitle = {{Interspeech 2020}},\npages = {616--620},\ndoi = {10.21437/Interspeech.2020-2357},\nissn = {2958-1796},\n}`\n\n**Cite as**: Ali, A., Renals, S. (2020) Word Error Rate Estimation Without ASR Output: e-WER2. Proc. Interspeech 2020, 616-620, doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2020-2357"}, {"url": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/59126899/how-can-i-evaluate-wer-word-error-rate-in-asr-automatic-speech-recognition", "title": "How Can I evaluate WER (Word Error Rate) in ASR ( Automatic ...", "content": "Kenny's user avatar\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nWord Error Rate is calculated based on formula:\n\nWord Error Rate = (Substitutions + Insertions + Deletions) / Number of Words Spoken\n\nIf we analyze this is very simple, we have first get the total number of Insertions, Deletions and substitutions in the ASR output by comparing with the actual transcript data (ground truth data). Now Insertion can happen at character level or word level or can be a combination of many characters, similarly deletion can also happen at multiple characters level, similarly in place of characters or words, new characters can also be wrongly inferenced which is basically substitution error. [...] To answer your specific questions:\n\n1. Punctuation & Capitalization:\nStrip punctuation and convert to lowercase before calculation.\n\n`from jiwer import wer\nimport string\ndef clean_text(text):\n# Remove punctuation and lowercase\ntext = text.lower()\ntext = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))\nreturn text\nreference = \"The cat, sat on the mat.\"\nhypothesis = \"The cat sit on the mat\"\nwer_score = wer(clean_text(reference), clean_text(hypothesis))`\n\n2. Substitutions, Insertions, Deletions:\nEach error type has equal weight in the standard WER formula.\n\n3. Manual Example:\n\n`Reference: \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nHypothesis: \"the cat sit on mat\"\nErrors:\n- \"sat\" → \"sit\" = 1 Substitution\n- \"the\" deleted = 1 Deletion\nWER = (1 + 0 + 1) / 6 = 0.333 = 33.3%` [...] Now the question arises how to identify these types of errors, for identifying these errors. For this Levenshtein distance metric is used.\n\nThe Levenshtein distance is a measurement of the differences between two “strings.” The strings are sequences of letters that make up the words in a transcription.\n\nLet’s look at some examples for better understanding\n\nAfter this get the total number of words and get the division done, this will give you WER\n\nNaval's user avatar\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nQuick Answer: Use the `jiwer` library for Python - it handles all the complexity for you:\n\n`jiwer`\n`from jiwer import wer\nreference = \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nhypothesis = \"the cat sit on the mat\"\nerror_rate = wer(reference, hypothesis)\nprint(f\"WER: {error_rate:.2%}\") # Output: WER: 16.67%`", "score": 0.3670439, "raw_content": "### [current community](https://stackoverflow.com)\n\n### your communities\n\n### [more stack exchange communities](https://stackexchange.com/sites)\n\nCommunities for your favorite technologies. [Explore all Collectives](/collectives-all)\n\nStack Overflow for Teams is now called **Stack Internal**. Bring the best of human thought and AI automation together at your work.\n\nBring the best of human thought and AI automation together at your work.\n[Learn more](https://stackoverflow.co/internal/?utm_medium=referral&utm_source=stackoverflow-community&utm_campaign=side-bar&utm_content=explore-teams-compact)\n\n##### Collectives™ on Stack Overflow\n\nFind centralized, trusted content and collaborate around the technologies you use most.\n\n**Stack Internal**\n\nKnowledge at work\n\nBring the best of human thought and AI automation together at your work.\n\n# [How Can I evaluate WER (Word Error Rate) in ASR ( Automatic Speech Recognition)?](/questions/59126899/how-can-i-evaluate-wer-word-error-rate-in-asr-automatic-speech-recognition)\n\nHow Can I evaluate WER (Word Error Rate) in ASR ( Automatic Speech Recognition)?\n\nFor Example, If I have (Human Ref. Translation) for the sentences and Output of ASR.\n\nI know the equation but I do not know how to calculate it. Do I enter punctuation marks such as a comma and full stop and so on in the calculation of WER?\n\nAs well as for sub, ins, and del of words. Is there a specific weight? Each of them when calculated in the equation?\n\nWould anyone who knows about how can we calculate WER for ASR.. please give me an example so I can calculate WER for ASR in multiple sentences that I have in my app\n\n![Randa Taiseer's user avatar](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-1PWGnqrJ0T4/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/ACHi3rdTWIdwBTPddRrn9KumTWkLF6Im4w/s64-rj/photo.jpg)\n\n## 5 Answers 5\n\nDo I enter punctuation marks such as a comma and full stop and so on in the calculation of WER?\n\nYou strip punctuation before calculation and convert everything to lowercase.\n\nWould anyone who knows about how can we calculate WER for ASR.. please give me an example so I can calculate WER for ASR in multiple sentences that I have in my app\n\nYou can use this Python package:\n\n<https://pypi.org/project/jiwer/>\n\nif you need other languages, let us know which ones.\n\n![Nikolay Shmyrev's user avatar](https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c6c16a68dfa5030f9b6df4d4ae4a337a?s=64&d=identicon&r=PG)\n\n## 1 Comment\n\nAdd a comment\n\n![](https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4713003a4a6967ae5048d2c9062fc6bf?s=48&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2)\n\na simple C++ implementation Based on Levenshtein distance,\njust a single file without any library.\n\n<https://github.com/alokprasad/asr-wer>\n\n![Alok Prasad's user avatar](https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-z9fJSHYTzU4/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAG7k/4kr-m1Is0TY/s64-rj/photo.jpg)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nRefer to this [repository](https://github.com/duckyngo/Word-Error-Rate-Visualization-with-Colab) to calculate the Word Error Rate (WER) of two strings with Colab.\n\nYou can also remove the punctuation when calculate WER by tick on the remote\\_punctuation checkbox.\n\n[![enter image description here](https://i.sstatic.net/oNRLQ.png)](https://i.sstatic.net/oNRLQ.png)\n\n![enter image description here](https://i.sstatic.net/oNRLQ.png)\n\nWord Error Rate Visualization with Colab: <https://github.com/duckyngo/Word-Error-Rate-Visualization-with-Colab>\n\n![Kenny's user avatar](https://i.sstatic.net/Mi9L0.jpg?s=64)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nWord Error Rate is calculated based on formula:\n\n**Word Error Rate = (Substitutions + Insertions + Deletions) / Number of Words Spoken**\n\nIf we analyze this is very simple, we have first get the total number of Insertions, Deletions and substitutions in the ASR output by comparing with the actual transcript data (ground truth data). Now Insertion can happen at character level or word level or can be a combination of many characters, similarly deletion can also happen at multiple characters level, similarly in place of characters or words, new characters can also be wrongly inferenced which is basically substitution error.\n\nNow the question arises how to identify these types of errors, for identifying these errors. For this **Levenshtein distance** metric is used.\n\nThe Levenshtein distance is a measurement of the differences between two “strings.” The strings are sequences of letters that make up the words in a transcription.\n\nLet’s look at some examples for better understanding\n\nAfter this get the total number of words and get the division done, this will give you WER\n\n![Naval's user avatar](https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e1f2e5223ae784673b11533900fae53c?s=64&d=identicon&r=PG)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\n**Quick Answer:** Use the `jiwer` library for Python - it handles all the complexity for you:\n\n`jiwer`\n`from jiwer import wer\nreference = \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nhypothesis = \"the cat sit on the mat\"\nerror_rate = wer(reference, hypothesis)\nprint(f\"WER: {error_rate:.2%}\") # Output: WER: 16.67%`\n\n**To answer your specific questions:**\n\n**1. Punctuation & Capitalization:**\nStrip punctuation and convert to lowercase **before** calculation.\n\n`from jiwer import wer\nimport string\ndef clean_text(text):\n# Remove punctuation and lowercase\ntext = text.lower()\ntext = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))\nreturn text\nreference = \"The cat, sat on the mat.\"\nhypothesis = \"The cat sit on the mat\"\nwer_score = wer(clean_text(reference), clean_text(hypothesis))`\n\n**2. Substitutions, Insertions, Deletions:**\nEach error type has **equal weight** in the standard WER formula.\n\n**3. Manual Example:**\n\n`Reference: \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nHypothesis: \"the cat sit on mat\"\nErrors:\n- \"sat\" → \"sit\" = 1 Substitution\n- \"the\" deleted = 1 Deletion\nWER = (1 + 0 + 1) / 6 = 0.333 = 33.3%`\n\nWhen I manually annotated transcriptions, I found it helpful to use a spreadsheet with columns for S, I, and D counts per sentence.\n\n![Erck's user avatar](https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJxk5wLQxUOTLesiDCUVgwzSMEE2n-a-tGH33lDrvA=k-s64)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\n## Your Answer\n\nThanks for cont